Pilumno...] Orithyia was wife of Boreas, who in Homer (Il. 20. 223) is the sire of the royal horses of Troy, just as Zephyrus is of the divine horses of Achilles (ΙΙ. 16. 150), early mythology—by a very natural image—personify- ing the winds as swift high-spirited steeds. Here Orithyia presents some of these half-divine steeds to the Italian deity Pilumnus, and he in turn bestows them on Turnus, who is his grandson (10. 76) or great-grandson (10. 619), Pilumnus is the brother of Picumnus (= Piens grandfather of Latinus, 7. 48).
